    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-09-30T18:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-09-30T18:00:00-05:00" n="441"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d441">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.20 (D) Regulations/4797: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Peru</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Norweb</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Lima</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-09-30T18:00:00-05:00"
                            >September 30, 1941—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 9:25 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>515. Reference Department’s 352, September 22.<note n="61" xml:id="d441fn61">Not
                        printed.</note> I am pleased to report that Metals Reserve representative
                    Smith this afternoon <pb facs="0543" n="535" xml:id="pg_535"/> signed the
                    agreement with the Director General of Finance. Official communiqué will be
                    published Thursday morning<note n="62" xml:id="d441fn62">October 2. See <hi
                            rend="italic">El Peruano Diario Oficial</hi>, October 3, 1941, p.
                        1.</note> containing résumé of agreement with short explanation of how basic
                    prices are determined and description of “floor under market principle”. It is
                    requested that you withhold publicity until Thursday morning, that is until
                    after the Government communiqué has been published here.</p>
                <p>According to a statement of the Finance Minister the Government of Peru has
                    decided to terminate molybdenum shipments to Japan as of today. British
                    diplomatic authorities in Lima informed me today that Great Britain will
                    definitely purchase the residue of the 1941 molybdenum contract with Japan as
                    well as the 83 metric tons salvaged from the German vessel <hi rend="italic"
                        >Monserrate.</hi>
                </p>
                <p>Chargeable to Metals Reserve Company.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Norweb</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
